column24: I did not have difficulty in swallowing, as I managed my stress levels effectively to prevent physical symptoms.
column25: I couldn't seem to get any enjoyment out of the extra workload, but I still found fulfillment in guiding students towards academic success.
column26: I was not particularly aware of the action of my heart in the absence of physical exertion, as I maintained a healthy work-life balance.
column27: I felt down-hearted and blue briefly, but I sought support from colleagues and found solace in the progress of my research projects.
column28: I found that I was very irritable in moments of high stress, but I made a conscious effort to address the root causes of my irritability.
column29: While I felt close to panic in challenging situations, I utilized coping strategies to manage my anxiety effectively.
column30: I found it hard to calm down after something upset me, but I practiced mindfulness and deep breathing techniques to regulate my emotions.
column31: I feared that I would be "thrown" by some trivial but unfamiliar task, but I approached such tasks with curiosity and a growth mindset.
column32: I was unable to become enthusiastic about minor administrative tasks, but I remained enthusiastic about teaching and research activities.
column33: I found it difficult to tolerate interruptions to what I was doing when focusing on important deadlines, but I managed to adapt and prioritize tasks effectively.
column34: I was in a state of nervous tension due to the increased workload and the need to provide additional support to struggling students.
column35: I did not feel I was pretty worthless, as I acknowledged my expertise and contributions to the field of psychology.
column36: I was intolerant of anything that kept me from completing my tasks efficiently, but I recognized the importance of flexibility in academia.
column37: I did not feel terrified, as I approached challenges with a sense of resilience and problem-solving skills.
column38: I could see nothing in the future to be hopeful about, but I remained optimistic about the potential growth and learning opportunities ahead.
column39: I felt that life was meaningful, especially when witnessing the progress and success of my students.
column40: I found myself getting agitated by the lack of understanding of fundamental concepts among students and the subsequent increase in workload.
column41: I was worried about situations in which I might make mistakes, but I approached such situations with a growth mindset and willingness to learn.
column42: I did not experience trembling in the hands, as I managed stress effectively through self-care practices and seeking support when needed.
column43: I found it difficult to work up the initiative to do things outside of my regular responsibilities, but I remained committed to my role as a professor and mentor.
